1
00:00:01,881 --> 00:00:04,441
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

2
00:00:37,601 --> 00:00:39,281
WOMEN: Happy birthday!

3
00:00:39,361 --> 00:00:41,801
I said no fuss.

4
00:00:42,081 --> 00:00:44,001
You have to celebrate
your birthday, Nani.

5
00:00:44,281 --> 00:00:47,041
I was the first woman
married in Pakistan.

6
00:00:47,561 --> 00:00:49,841
Now, look at me, in a wheelchair,

7
00:00:50,201 --> 00:00:51,841
and being fed shop-bought cake.

8
00:00:52,241 --> 00:00:53,521
That's a nice cake.

9
00:00:53,801 --> 00:00:56,081
"The first woman married in Pakistan,"
Did you know this?

10
00:00:56,281 --> 00:00:58,961
And I was the first Muslim woman

11
00:00:59,121 --> 00:01:01,881
to work in a textile mill
in South Yorkshire.

12
00:01:02,561 --> 00:01:04,681
Granddad taking you dancing
every Wednesday night.

13
00:01:04,801 --> 00:01:05,801
NANI: Oh!

14
00:01:06,681 --> 00:01:08,721
I so miss that man.

15
00:01:09,961 --> 00:01:13,521
Now, I want to give you these things
before it's too late.

16
00:01:13,641 --> 00:01:15,321
Najia, these are some letters

17
00:01:15,441 --> 00:01:17,161
your father wrote to me
when he was away.

18
00:01:17,241 --> 00:01:19,521
-Don't read the filthy bits.
-(BOTH LAUGHING)

19
00:01:20,041 --> 00:01:23,321
Sonya, this is a present
your grandfather gave me.

20
00:01:23,961 --> 00:01:26,921
I can't remember why, but it's nice.

21
00:01:31,041 --> 00:01:34,641
And, now, Yasmin,
my favourite granddaughter.

22
00:01:35,321 --> 00:01:37,881
What? Mummy, what?
I've told you about that.

23
00:01:38,401 --> 00:01:39,441
I want you to have this.

24
00:01:43,881 --> 00:01:45,881
Thank you. Was it Granddad's?

25
00:01:47,401 --> 00:01:48,681
I can get it fixed, if you like.

26
00:01:49,001 --> 00:01:50,641
It must never be fixed.

27
00:01:51,441 --> 00:01:52,441
Why not?

28
00:01:52,641 --> 00:01:54,241
I don't want to talk about it any more.

29
00:01:54,521 --> 00:01:55,721
Nani, please.

30
00:01:55,881 --> 00:01:57,641
NANI: You won't understand.

31
00:01:59,441 --> 00:02:02,081
I have such stories I could tell you.

32
00:02:02,201 --> 00:02:03,641
And we want to hear them, really.

33
00:02:04,241 --> 00:02:06,001
If you don't tell us, we won't know.

34
00:02:07,041 --> 00:02:08,361
Your life's our heritage.

35
00:02:09,561 --> 00:02:12,041
When you're older, maybe.

36
00:02:15,401 --> 00:02:16,441
DOCTOR: I know what you're asking,

37
00:02:17,001 --> 00:02:19,121
but family history and time travel,
very tricky.

38
00:02:19,321 --> 00:02:20,321
Just for an hour.

39
00:02:20,401 --> 00:02:21,721
-See her from a distance.
-(GRUNTS)

40
00:02:21,841 --> 00:02:23,681
What's the point in having a mate
with a time machine if you can't

41
00:02:23,761 --> 00:02:25,201
nip back and see your gran
when she was younger?

42
00:02:25,921 --> 00:02:27,161
(SCREAMS)

43
00:02:27,921 --> 00:02:28,961
Erm...

44
00:02:33,361 --> 00:02:34,601
Have you got a time or place?

45
00:02:34,761 --> 00:02:36,601
I know she lived in Lahore in the '50s.

46
00:02:37,481 --> 00:02:39,241
-But other than that...
-I mean, I could.

47
00:02:39,881 --> 00:02:40,961
I shouldn't.

48
00:02:41,641 --> 00:02:44,241
Unless... No. Too unpredictable.

49
00:02:44,641 --> 00:02:46,161
-Could what?
-It's a risk.

50
00:02:46,441 --> 00:02:48,441
Oh, like none of our other trips
have ever been risky.

51
00:02:49,121 --> 00:02:52,681
I have apologised for the death-eye
turtle army. Profusely.

52
00:02:53,601 --> 00:02:56,641
I suppose I could loop this into
the TARDIS' telepathic circuits.

53
00:02:57,001 --> 00:02:58,361
This thing's telepathic, too?

54
00:02:58,841 --> 00:03:00,401
Don't call her a thing, Graham.

55
00:03:00,601 --> 00:03:02,921
And, yes, she does have
telepathic navigation, sort of.

56
00:03:03,161 --> 00:03:07,001
Shorthand for a very complicated process
which is way beyond your understanding.

57
00:03:07,081 --> 00:03:09,361
Ta very much.
I only hang around here to be insulted.

58
00:03:09,801 --> 00:03:11,601
Any object amasses all sorts

59
00:03:11,681 --> 00:03:14,161
of fragmentary spatio-temporal particles
through its life.

60
00:03:14,761 --> 00:03:16,881
The TARDIS can read it like date stamps.

61
00:03:17,641 --> 00:03:18,761
What do you two reckon?

62
00:03:19,041 --> 00:03:20,521
Oh, yeah, I love it. Pakistan.

63
00:03:20,601 --> 00:03:22,361
Never been there before.
Another one off the bucket list.

64
00:03:22,441 --> 00:03:23,721
As long as there's no killer turtles.

65
00:03:23,801 --> 00:03:25,001
Yeah, I'm well up for it.

66
00:03:25,881 --> 00:03:28,001
Hmm. One hour. No...

67
00:03:28,081 --> 00:03:29,081
-ALL: Interfering.
-...interfering.

68
00:03:31,881 --> 00:03:33,681
(TARDIS POWERING UP)

69
00:03:34,081 --> 00:03:36,121
Go on. You know you can do it.

70
00:03:37,521 --> 00:03:38,761
Bit of a punt.

71
00:03:44,441 --> 00:03:47,361
(TARDIS WHOOSHING)

72
00:03:55,361 --> 00:03:57,441
DOCTOR: Whoa! Nice!

73
00:03:58,321 --> 00:04:00,721
I thought Lahore was a city.
This ain't a city.

74
00:04:00,801 --> 00:04:01,841
(GASPS)

75
00:04:05,361 --> 00:04:06,841
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)

76
00:04:11,961 --> 00:04:13,401
TARDIS readings are all over the shop.

77
00:04:14,001 --> 00:04:15,321
Looks pretty, northern Punjab.

78
00:04:15,521 --> 00:04:18,001
(DISTORTED VOICE SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

79
00:04:19,441 --> 00:04:20,761
(COW MOOING)

80
00:04:20,841 --> 00:04:22,001
Hey, get off the road!

81
00:04:22,641 --> 00:04:24,761
Really sorry. Bit of a wobble.

82
00:04:25,401 --> 00:04:26,441
What just happened?

83
00:04:26,801 --> 00:04:29,121
Not sure. But I didn't like it at all.

84
00:04:29,521 --> 00:04:30,921
(MOOING)

85
00:04:31,241 --> 00:04:32,961
Sorry, mate, er, we're just getting
our bearings.

86
00:04:33,041 --> 00:04:34,201
We're not from around here.

87
00:04:34,281 --> 00:04:35,561
Yeah, no kidding.

88
00:04:35,681 --> 00:04:37,281
Your Punjabi's not bad
for foreigners, though.

89
00:04:37,681 --> 00:04:38,881
You need to be careful.

90
00:04:39,161 --> 00:04:40,601
These roads aren't safe right now.

91
00:04:41,721 --> 00:04:43,241
We're actually looking for a woman

92
00:04:43,561 --> 00:04:44,721
by the name of Umbreen.

93
00:04:45,241 --> 00:04:46,561
Right, Umbreen.

94
00:04:47,001 --> 00:04:48,001
What for?

95
00:04:48,281 --> 00:04:49,361
-We're family.
-We're friends.

96
00:04:50,761 --> 00:04:51,761
Family friends.

97
00:04:53,161 --> 00:04:55,681
We're on our way to say hello.
Bit of a surprise.

98
00:04:57,001 --> 00:04:58,401
But we agreed...

99
00:04:59,041 --> 00:05:00,321
Er, okay, get in.

100
00:05:00,761 --> 00:05:02,561
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

101
00:05:07,321 --> 00:05:08,641
CART DRIVER: Okay?
GRAHAM: Yeah.

102
00:05:08,801 --> 00:05:10,121
GRAHAM: Thank you.

103
00:05:10,201 --> 00:05:11,201
You all right?

104
00:05:11,401 --> 00:05:13,441
I think so. Probably.

105
00:05:13,841 --> 00:05:15,121
I don't know.

106
00:05:15,281 --> 00:05:18,081
Like I intercepted something.
In my brain.

107
00:05:20,281 --> 00:05:22,161
So, what, you're a flower merchant?

108
00:05:22,241 --> 00:05:24,081
Er, pretty much, right now.

109
00:05:25,801 --> 00:05:27,121
-(COW MOOING)
-Why isn't it safe on the roads?

110
00:05:27,801 --> 00:05:29,361
Running transport now, Prem?

111
00:05:29,841 --> 00:05:30,841
Want a ride with us, Sadhu?

112
00:05:31,081 --> 00:05:32,241
I can take one more.

113
00:05:32,841 --> 00:05:33,841
What's wrong with your feet?

114
00:05:34,561 --> 00:05:35,561
You young people,

115
00:05:36,081 --> 00:05:37,121
always such a rush.

116
00:05:37,321 --> 00:05:38,721
Walking served me all my life.

117
00:05:39,401 --> 00:05:41,601
I'll be there, don't you worry.
(CHUCKLES)

118
00:05:42,201 --> 00:05:43,201
We'll be ready.

119
00:05:44,321 --> 00:05:46,601
I'm late. Umbreen's gonna kill me.

120
00:06:32,121 --> 00:06:33,121
You're late!

121
00:06:34,361 --> 00:06:35,361
And who are they?

122
00:06:35,641 --> 00:06:37,081
They're your family, Umbreen.

123
00:06:39,121 --> 00:06:40,121
What?

124
00:06:41,121 --> 00:06:42,281
Oh, my God.

125
00:06:42,881 --> 00:06:43,881
You're Umbreen.

126
00:06:45,121 --> 00:06:46,401
You look amazing.

127
00:06:47,321 --> 00:06:48,401
What are you doing here?

128
00:06:48,961 --> 00:06:50,001
I live here.

129
00:06:50,161 --> 00:06:51,241
On a farm?

130
00:06:51,481 --> 00:06:52,481
But I thought...

131
00:06:52,881 --> 00:06:55,361
It doesn't matter.
I'm so happy to see you.

132
00:06:56,161 --> 00:06:58,641
So, Yaz, you should probably
explain who we are.

133
00:06:59,041 --> 00:07:02,041
Sorry, yeah. Excited.

134
00:07:02,601 --> 00:07:03,681
Uncle Malik.

135
00:07:04,441 --> 00:07:06,001
You know Uncle Malik.

136
00:07:06,561 --> 00:07:07,801
There are loads of Uncle Maliks.

137
00:07:07,921 --> 00:07:09,801
Exactly. Well,

138
00:07:10,041 --> 00:07:12,281
the one from about 15 valleys over,

139
00:07:12,641 --> 00:07:16,401
I'm that Uncle Malik's third cousin's
younger sister, Yaz.

140
00:07:17,321 --> 00:07:20,481
And these are my friends, Ryan,
Graham, and the Doctor.

141
00:07:20,561 --> 00:07:21,561
-Hi.
-Hello.

142
00:07:21,641 --> 00:07:22,881
All the way from England.

143
00:07:23,081 --> 00:07:24,801
You might want to keep that to yourself
right now.

144
00:07:25,841 --> 00:07:26,841
-UMBREEN: Right.
-What?

145
00:07:27,041 --> 00:07:29,921
It's just, we weren't expecting you,
or anyone.

146
00:07:30,921 --> 00:07:33,161
Uncle Malik's not coming to the wedding
as well, is he?

147
00:07:33,441 --> 00:07:35,961
-There's a wedding?
-Which is why we're here.

148
00:07:36,241 --> 00:07:37,761
Bringing wedding best wishes.

149
00:07:38,041 --> 00:07:40,281
Erm, when... When's the big day again?

150
00:07:40,601 --> 00:07:42,121
-Tomorrow.
-YASMIN: Amazing.

151
00:07:42,361 --> 00:07:43,681
I can't wait to meet the groom.

152
00:07:44,001 --> 00:07:45,441
You already have.

153
00:07:45,841 --> 00:07:47,801
Remember me? Car, flowers?

154
00:07:48,481 --> 00:07:50,681
-Marrying Umbreen.
-No.

155
00:07:51,961 --> 00:07:53,081
You can't be.

156
00:07:54,041 --> 00:07:56,321
-You're not my...
-A wedding in the Punjab. Bring it on.

157
00:07:57,161 --> 00:07:58,321
I love a wedding. Don't we, boys?

158
00:07:58,641 --> 00:08:00,921
Oh, yeah, I can go to a wedding
every day if I could. Yeah.

159
00:08:01,081 --> 00:08:03,121
Hey, do you need a singer?
I know all the classics.

160
00:08:03,201 --> 00:08:05,361
-Well, latest hits to you lot.
-Er, don't ever let him sing.

161
00:08:05,561 --> 00:08:06,601
We won't be staying long anyway.

162
00:08:06,681 --> 00:08:09,401
Just wanted to convey our best wishes

163
00:08:10,001 --> 00:08:11,241
and then head off.

164
00:08:11,961 --> 00:08:14,001
MAN: Hi, I thought I saw some people
in the cart.

165
00:08:14,201 --> 00:08:15,681
Sorry about his driving.

166
00:08:16,161 --> 00:08:18,281
My baby brother thinks he can do
everything better than me.

167
00:08:24,161 --> 00:08:25,161
I'm Manish.

168
00:08:25,481 --> 00:08:27,561
Come, all of you. It's being announced!

169
00:08:28,161 --> 00:08:29,441
UMBREEN: Coming, Mum.

170
00:08:30,241 --> 00:08:31,241
Who are they?

171
00:08:31,321 --> 00:08:32,321
What's happening?

172
00:08:32,401 --> 00:08:33,921
MANISH: Everyone's waiting
for the announcement.

173
00:08:34,001 --> 00:08:35,641
But I've got advanced information.

174
00:08:40,001 --> 00:08:41,001
DOCTOR: Okay.

175
00:08:41,841 --> 00:08:42,921
Number one,

176
00:08:43,361 --> 00:08:45,121
the man Umbreen is about to marry
is not my granddad.

177
00:08:45,601 --> 00:08:47,081
-Defo? Totally sure?
-YASMIN: Yes.

178
00:08:47,521 --> 00:08:49,201
For starters, Prem's a Hindu name.

179
00:08:49,441 --> 00:08:50,441
We're Muslim.

180
00:08:50,601 --> 00:08:53,601
And he doesn't look
anything like the photos. It's not him.

181
00:08:53,721 --> 00:08:55,441
And that Umbreen, she's your nan, right?

182
00:08:55,561 --> 00:08:57,241
Yeah, she does look like the photo.

183
00:08:57,721 --> 00:09:00,161
But Prem's wearing the watch
your nani gave you in the future.

184
00:09:00,361 --> 00:09:02,961
So what, she had a secret Hindu
first husband?

185
00:09:03,841 --> 00:09:06,121
Er, Doc, I reckon an hour's
nearly up, mate.

186
00:09:06,241 --> 00:09:07,241
Yeah.

187
00:09:07,321 --> 00:09:09,281
We can't go. I came here for answers.

188
00:09:09,561 --> 00:09:10,841
All I've got is more questions.

189
00:09:10,921 --> 00:09:12,241
I knew this would happen.

190
00:09:12,321 --> 00:09:13,601
MANISH: Can anyone
help me with this?

191
00:09:13,721 --> 00:09:15,281
I'll help. I'm Yaz.

192
00:09:15,401 --> 00:09:16,721
MANISH: Great, thanks, Yaz.

193
00:09:16,801 --> 00:09:18,321
Big moment.
You won't forget this in a hurry.

194
00:09:19,761 --> 00:09:21,281
You're right there.

195
00:09:21,961 --> 00:09:23,081
I shouldn't have come.

196
00:09:23,521 --> 00:09:24,921
I'm too nice.

197
00:09:25,001 --> 00:09:26,601
This is what happens
when you try to be nice.

198
00:09:28,281 --> 00:09:29,961
Who wants to know
what they're listening to in there?

199
00:09:30,961 --> 00:09:31,961
-Yup.
-Yup.

200
00:09:33,641 --> 00:09:34,841
BRITISH NEWSREADER: (ON RADIO)
After much delay

201
00:09:34,921 --> 00:09:36,881
and amid escalating communal violence,

202
00:09:36,961 --> 00:09:40,001
Lord Mountbatten has finally released
the specific details

203
00:09:40,081 --> 00:09:42,081
of the border which will separate
the two countries.

204
00:09:42,161 --> 00:09:43,601
What borders are they talking about?

205
00:09:43,961 --> 00:09:45,001
Pakistan.

206
00:09:45,521 --> 00:09:47,761
Today, India's officially
cut into pieces.

207
00:09:48,921 --> 00:09:50,481
It's the 17th of August.

208
00:09:50,841 --> 00:09:52,481
And still, you want to go ahead?

209
00:09:52,761 --> 00:09:55,281
Nothing changes, Mum.
We knew this was coming.

210
00:09:55,481 --> 00:09:58,241
Sorry, I don't mean to sound stupid,
what year is it, exactly?

211
00:09:58,561 --> 00:10:01,801
Same year you have in England, 1947.

212
00:10:02,841 --> 00:10:04,041
Partition.

213
00:10:04,561 --> 00:10:06,401
We're in the middle
of the partition of India.

214
00:10:08,121 --> 00:10:09,721
MANISH: Three, two, one.

215
00:10:10,481 --> 00:10:11,841
Is it for the celebrations?

216
00:10:12,121 --> 00:10:14,201
Big celebrations. Welcome to the border.

217
00:10:14,361 --> 00:10:16,641
-PREM: Manish.
-Where India ends and our future begins.

218
00:10:17,001 --> 00:10:18,001
PREM: What are you doing?

219
00:10:18,081 --> 00:10:20,281
Yaz, hi. (PANTING)

220
00:10:20,361 --> 00:10:23,921
Quick sidebar, August, 1947, Partition.

221
00:10:24,241 --> 00:10:25,721
The borders have just been announced.

222
00:10:26,161 --> 00:10:27,601
India. Pakistan.

223
00:10:27,921 --> 00:10:29,681
It's not just the land
that gets divided.

224
00:10:29,841 --> 00:10:31,201
Rioting in the cities.

225
00:10:31,681 --> 00:10:33,961
Tens of millions of people
about to be displaced.

226
00:10:34,081 --> 00:10:35,721
More than a million about to die.

227
00:10:36,001 --> 00:10:39,641
Doc, meanwhile, her Nan's about
to get married, but not to her Granddad.

228
00:10:39,881 --> 00:10:41,521
I'm thinking
that hour's well up, now.

229
00:10:41,761 --> 00:10:44,081
You can't know the borders.
It's only just been announced!

230
00:10:44,281 --> 00:10:47,001
The maps were leaked weeks ago.
I got one from my sources.

231
00:10:47,201 --> 00:10:50,481
Your sources must be wrong, because
you've just put my house in Pakistan.

232
00:10:51,801 --> 00:10:52,961
With the other Muslims.

233
00:10:54,681 --> 00:10:56,481
But you get a fresh start.

234
00:10:56,561 --> 00:10:58,081
Manish, you need to slow down.

235
00:10:58,281 --> 00:11:01,681
Pakistan is somewhere for Muslims
if they want to go.

236
00:11:02,001 --> 00:11:03,081
I'm not saying you have to go,

237
00:11:03,361 --> 00:11:05,961
but Pakistan
is being created for Muslims.

238
00:11:06,201 --> 00:11:07,801
Hindus have India, we both feel safe.

239
00:11:07,921 --> 00:11:10,281
Don't reduce it to that, brother.
It's not that simple.

240
00:11:11,441 --> 00:11:13,401
But I get you have a hard decision
if you're married.

241
00:11:15,801 --> 00:11:18,241
The land belongs to everyone,
has done for centuries.

242
00:11:18,321 --> 00:11:19,761
One day doesn't change that.

243
00:11:20,601 --> 00:11:23,081
I love you, brother, but you're wrong.

244
00:11:26,201 --> 00:11:27,361
(GROANS)

245
00:11:27,441 --> 00:11:29,641
(DISTORTED VOICE SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

246
00:11:29,801 --> 00:11:30,801
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

247
00:11:31,081 --> 00:11:32,961
Look, demons!

248
00:11:38,081 --> 00:11:39,401
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)

249
00:11:40,201 --> 00:11:43,321
I told you this would happen.
I told you these days were cursed!

250
00:11:44,401 --> 00:11:45,761
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER BEEPING)

251
00:11:47,681 --> 00:11:48,681
It's gone!

252
00:11:50,401 --> 00:11:52,481
Not far. We'll deal with this. Come on.

253
00:11:57,401 --> 00:11:59,281
-(WHIRRING)
-Find the signal. They didn't go far.

254
00:12:00,001 --> 00:12:01,841
(GASPS)

255
00:12:02,401 --> 00:12:03,841
-(HIGH-PITCHED WHIRRING)
-ALIEN: Stay away.

256
00:12:04,161 --> 00:12:05,841
-(SCREAMS)
-(DISTORTED VOICE SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

257
00:12:06,801 --> 00:12:07,801
(VOICE STOPS)

258
00:12:11,241 --> 00:12:13,321
-Did I get them?
-I don't think so.

259
00:12:13,561 --> 00:12:15,161
They move faster than your bullet.

260
00:12:17,041 --> 00:12:18,441
-What were they?
-PREM: Bhakti!

261
00:12:20,481 --> 00:12:21,721
They killed him.

262
00:12:23,961 --> 00:12:24,961
He was your man on the road.

263
00:12:25,201 --> 00:12:27,201
He's a holy man. A sadhu.

264
00:12:27,681 --> 00:12:29,361
-Everyone knows him as Bhakti.
-(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)

265
00:12:29,481 --> 00:12:31,521
Umbreen and I asked him
to bless our marriage.

266
00:12:31,921 --> 00:12:33,921
-Why would they kill him?
-DOCTOR: I don't know.

267
00:12:34,201 --> 00:12:35,761
But what I also don't understand is,

268
00:12:35,961 --> 00:12:39,921
you just saw something not of this world
and you took it right in your stride.

269
00:12:40,601 --> 00:12:41,601
Why's that, Prem?

270
00:12:42,921 --> 00:12:44,081
I've seen them before.

271
00:12:46,721 --> 00:12:48,441
Where have you seen them before?

272
00:12:49,721 --> 00:12:50,721
(EXHALES SHARPLY)

273
00:12:57,921 --> 00:12:59,041
Who are you?

274
00:13:01,081 --> 00:13:03,401
You say you're Umbreen's family,
but clearly you're not.

275
00:13:04,521 --> 00:13:06,241
And you ran at those demons
like you didn't care.

276
00:13:07,081 --> 00:13:08,441
I don't think they're demons.

277
00:13:11,361 --> 00:13:12,961
Why should I trust what you think?

278
00:13:13,241 --> 00:13:15,241
Because we've got experience
with impossible creatures

279
00:13:15,321 --> 00:13:18,281
and because we ask questions like,
"What is this substance on his body?"

280
00:13:22,281 --> 00:13:23,561
And things are getting even weirder.

281
00:13:23,641 --> 00:13:25,121
GRAHAM: You think that's what
they used to kill him?

282
00:13:25,201 --> 00:13:26,361
-(WHIRRING)
-Some sort of fast-dissolving

283
00:13:26,441 --> 00:13:27,441
poisonous dust?

284
00:13:27,841 --> 00:13:29,441
It doesn't read like he was poisoned.

285
00:13:30,121 --> 00:13:31,201
I don't understand.

286
00:13:31,721 --> 00:13:33,241
So, what are we going to tell
the others back there?

287
00:13:34,281 --> 00:13:35,521
They don't have to know.

288
00:13:35,681 --> 00:13:37,521
Hasna already thinks
the marriage is cursed.

289
00:13:37,881 --> 00:13:40,601
Umbreen doesn't need anything else
to worry about, and Manish,

290
00:13:42,081 --> 00:13:43,681
who knows what he thinks these days.

291
00:13:44,121 --> 00:13:46,281
I was away from him for too long.
Fighting in the war.

292
00:13:46,441 --> 00:13:49,001
By the time I got back,
Manish wasn't my baby brother any more.

293
00:13:49,601 --> 00:13:50,801
YASMIN: People grow up.

294
00:13:51,281 --> 00:13:53,281
We all have to find our own way.

295
00:13:54,921 --> 00:13:56,801
Some of us need more guidance
than others.

296
00:13:57,881 --> 00:13:59,281
This fella needs to be laid to rest.

297
00:13:59,361 --> 00:14:01,241
Why don't we go and get the others
to help,

298
00:14:01,561 --> 00:14:02,961
but not let on what happened.

299
00:14:06,641 --> 00:14:08,801
Oh accordion waves.

300
00:14:09,361 --> 00:14:13,721
Which could mean
a dormant octonic engine nearby.

301
00:14:14,281 --> 00:14:15,281
What's she saying?

302
00:14:15,361 --> 00:14:17,121
If I had to guess, I think
we're going demon hunting.

303
00:14:17,721 --> 00:14:18,961
Gold star for Ryan.

304
00:14:19,081 --> 00:14:21,081
Oh, wait. Was I awarding points?

305
00:14:21,481 --> 00:14:23,041
I forgot about the points!

306
00:14:23,481 --> 00:14:24,481
I'm coming with you.

307
00:14:24,681 --> 00:14:26,401
-No.
-PREM: I know this forest.

308
00:14:26,481 --> 00:14:27,681
I can help.

309
00:14:29,121 --> 00:14:30,721
Okay. Yaz!

310
00:14:31,721 --> 00:14:33,161
Be careful what you say back there.

311
00:14:33,321 --> 00:14:34,721
The wrong word in the wrong moment,

312
00:14:34,841 --> 00:14:37,641
you can interfere yourself
out of existence. Do you understand?

313
00:14:38,401 --> 00:14:39,801
You know there are aliens here, right?

314
00:14:39,921 --> 00:14:42,561
In the Punjab during Partition.
And you're worried about me being gobby?

315
00:14:42,641 --> 00:14:43,801
Tread softly.

316
00:14:43,961 --> 00:14:45,361
You're treading on your own history.

317
00:14:50,201 --> 00:14:52,281
-(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)
-I like this.

318
00:14:52,841 --> 00:14:56,081
Traipsing through the forest, alongside
the British, looking for the enemy.

319
00:14:57,321 --> 00:14:58,361
I've done enough of that.

320
00:14:58,681 --> 00:15:00,601
Although, maybe you're my enemy now,

321
00:15:00,681 --> 00:15:02,401
for the mess you just made
of my country.

322
00:15:03,401 --> 00:15:05,441
Carving it up, slapdash, in six weeks.

323
00:15:06,921 --> 00:15:08,241
Gonna run off home now, are you?

324
00:15:08,881 --> 00:15:10,841
I'll make a note of your thoughts
and pass 'em on to Mountbatten

325
00:15:10,961 --> 00:15:12,161
if I ever bump into him again.

326
00:15:12,881 --> 00:15:14,841
These demon things,
you've seen them before,

327
00:15:14,961 --> 00:15:16,761
or do you reckon they're here
because of the Partition?

328
00:15:17,521 --> 00:15:19,521
I don't know. I need to find out.

329
00:15:19,641 --> 00:15:22,201
Then he's got one up on you
if he's seen them before you.

330
00:15:23,841 --> 00:15:25,161
What's your demon-tracker saying?

331
00:15:26,201 --> 00:15:27,321
It's saying...

332
00:15:32,521 --> 00:15:33,961
Hello.

333
00:15:34,361 --> 00:15:35,801
-(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)
-What is that?

334
00:15:36,241 --> 00:15:37,441
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER BEEPING)

335
00:15:38,081 --> 00:15:39,201
It seems like a Transmat

336
00:15:39,401 --> 00:15:40,401
doorway.

337
00:15:40,521 --> 00:15:41,841
(RIFLE CLICKS)

338
00:15:42,161 --> 00:15:44,281
Nice. That was cool.

339
00:15:45,401 --> 00:15:47,081
What. Just. Happened?

340
00:15:48,201 --> 00:15:50,121
We were in the forest, and now we're...

341
00:15:51,841 --> 00:15:52,841
Really not.

342
00:15:52,921 --> 00:15:55,321
Short answer, we got dragged
through a doorway,

343
00:15:55,401 --> 00:15:57,121
-into...
-A demon's lair.

344
00:15:57,281 --> 00:15:59,161
I wouldn't put it quite
like that, but you're getting the gist.

345
00:15:59,241 --> 00:16:00,761
-(WHIRRING)
-Spaceship, though, right?

346
00:16:00,841 --> 00:16:03,041
-(SONIC SCREWDRIVER BEEPING)
-I can't get a read on anything.

347
00:16:03,401 --> 00:16:04,521
It's beautiful.

348
00:16:04,881 --> 00:16:07,961
Yeah, you're right. It really is.

349
00:16:08,521 --> 00:16:11,161
They can surprise you, demons.

350
00:16:11,241 --> 00:16:13,001
Hey, do you think they're here?

351
00:16:13,281 --> 00:16:14,841
I'm not getting any life signals.

352
00:16:15,081 --> 00:16:16,921
Maybe they're out shopping.

353
00:16:17,201 --> 00:16:18,281
Catching a movie.

354
00:16:18,721 --> 00:16:20,721
Bowling. Some races like bowling.

355
00:16:20,921 --> 00:16:22,361
I'm talking to confront my latent worry.

356
00:16:22,561 --> 00:16:23,561
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)

357
00:16:23,961 --> 00:16:25,241
I know. I got that now.

358
00:16:25,801 --> 00:16:28,321
Oh, come on!
One of these things must unlock it.

359
00:16:29,601 --> 00:16:31,041
-(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)
- (DEVICE WHIRRING)

360
00:16:31,121 --> 00:16:33,041
Hey, that worked. (CHUCKLES)

361
00:16:34,001 --> 00:16:35,561
-What is it?
-Exactly what I wanted.

362
00:16:35,921 --> 00:16:39,001
Craft spec, species, data, bio-ID.

363
00:16:42,241 --> 00:16:43,961
-(GASPS)
-RYAN: What?

364
00:16:44,601 --> 00:16:46,241
What have you seen, Doctor?

365
00:16:49,361 --> 00:16:51,321
This is a Thijarian hive.

366
00:16:51,841 --> 00:16:53,441
Is that a good thing or a bad thing?

367
00:16:53,721 --> 00:16:55,441
Thijarians are assassins.

368
00:16:55,521 --> 00:16:57,401
Right, so that's basically
a bad thing, then.

369
00:16:57,921 --> 00:16:59,561
I've heard about them.
Never come across them.

370
00:16:59,641 --> 00:17:01,441
They're one of the ancient species,

371
00:17:01,561 --> 00:17:04,761
evolved themselves into the deadliest
assassins in the known universe.

372
00:17:05,321 --> 00:17:06,481
-(PANTING)
-(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)

373
00:17:09,841 --> 00:17:11,841
-He was their target.
-DOCTOR: Why, though?

374
00:17:12,001 --> 00:17:15,561
Why would the Thijarians target
a holy man in the 1940s?

375
00:17:16,241 --> 00:17:19,001
Wait, you said you'd seen them before,
where?

376
00:17:19,801 --> 00:17:20,921
I don't want to talk about that.

377
00:17:21,081 --> 00:17:22,161
It could be important.

378
00:17:22,241 --> 00:17:23,321
I don't want any of this.

379
00:17:25,281 --> 00:17:26,761
I'm supposed to be married tomorrow.

380
00:17:26,841 --> 00:17:28,641
Mate, the Doctor's right.

381
00:17:28,721 --> 00:17:31,081
We can help you,
but you have to trust us.

382
00:17:32,401 --> 00:17:33,681
Where did you see them?

383
00:17:38,001 --> 00:17:39,001
In Singapore.

384
00:17:40,841 --> 00:17:42,961
Our section had found
a boat to escape on.

385
00:17:43,321 --> 00:17:45,681
-(EXPLOSION IN DISTANCE)
-But I'd signed up with Kunal.

386
00:17:46,481 --> 00:17:48,441
I wasn't going to leave
without him at my side.

387
00:17:48,921 --> 00:17:50,801
Kunal!

388
00:17:52,641 --> 00:17:53,881
Kunal?

389
00:17:54,361 --> 00:17:56,081
That's where I saw the demons.

390
00:17:57,281 --> 00:17:59,441
Standing over my older brother's
dead body.

391
00:18:09,001 --> 00:18:10,161
(WHOOSHING)

392
00:18:17,321 --> 00:18:19,881
I lost them in the haze
as the evacuation sounded.

393
00:18:20,241 --> 00:18:21,961
(ALARM BLARING)

394
00:18:37,121 --> 00:18:38,121
(PANTING)

395
00:18:38,281 --> 00:18:39,281
Left his body there.

396
00:18:43,601 --> 00:18:44,921
I couldn't save him.

397
00:18:47,081 --> 00:18:48,481
Why are they here?

398
00:18:50,081 --> 00:18:51,881
How did we bring demons on ourselves?

399
00:18:55,241 --> 00:18:56,961
DOCTOR: I don't know,
but we'll find out.

400
00:18:57,161 --> 00:18:59,361
And we'll protect you. All of you.

401
00:18:59,921 --> 00:19:00,921
What if you can't?

402
00:19:02,921 --> 00:19:06,001
Oh, er, hey, hey. Look at this. Erm...

403
00:19:08,481 --> 00:19:10,081
That was the stuff
that was on the holy man's body.

404
00:19:11,001 --> 00:19:12,321
The stuff that they used to kill him.

405
00:19:12,641 --> 00:19:14,721
Oh, taking a look at that.

406
00:19:15,361 --> 00:19:16,481
(ALARM BLARING)

407
00:19:16,561 --> 00:19:19,041
Over keen, should've thought
about that Uh...

408
00:19:19,801 --> 00:19:20,801
-They're here!
-(HIGH-PITCHED RINGING)

409
00:19:21,081 --> 00:19:23,241
THIJARIAN: You have desecrated the hive.

410
00:19:23,401 --> 00:19:25,081
-(ALL GROANING)
-The hive is sacred.

411
00:19:25,161 --> 00:19:27,281
Do you have to push your words
into our heads like that?

412
00:19:27,361 --> 00:19:28,801
Because it really hurts.

413
00:19:29,081 --> 00:19:33,241
And, no, we haven't, actually, it's you
who are desecrating this planet.

414
00:19:33,441 --> 00:19:37,921
I know who you are, I know what you do,
and it's not happening here.

415
00:19:38,081 --> 00:19:41,881
Leave these people alone.
They're under my protection now.

416
00:19:42,121 --> 00:19:43,921
You cannot prevent this.

417
00:19:44,361 --> 00:19:45,801
You just watch me.

418
00:19:46,201 --> 00:19:47,201
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)

419
00:19:47,441 --> 00:19:48,721
(GASPING)

420
00:19:49,761 --> 00:19:51,081
Get out of the forest!

421
00:19:52,401 --> 00:19:53,401
What?

422
00:20:00,201 --> 00:20:02,921
Miniaturised Transmat locks. Clever.

423
00:20:03,081 --> 00:20:05,281
Also, confiscated.

424
00:20:05,521 --> 00:20:06,521
See ya!

425
00:20:09,561 --> 00:20:10,561
(BOTH GASP)

426
00:20:10,921 --> 00:20:12,841
-What just happened?
-No idea.

427
00:20:12,921 --> 00:20:14,921
But the Doctor said,
"Get out of the forest." Come on.

428
00:20:17,921 --> 00:20:18,921
(PANTING)

429
00:20:20,281 --> 00:20:21,681
(GASPS) And another one!

430
00:20:24,601 --> 00:20:25,601
Did you know him well?

431
00:20:25,841 --> 00:20:28,721
Bhakti taught me the scriptures.
How did he die?

432
00:20:29,761 --> 00:20:32,041
-We're not exactly sure.
-HASNA: Where's Prem?

433
00:20:32,761 --> 00:20:34,081
And your other friends?

434
00:20:34,721 --> 00:20:36,921
Seeing if they can find out
any more about what happened.

435
00:20:37,961 --> 00:20:39,161
HASNA: Your family, Manish,

436
00:20:39,681 --> 00:20:40,681
cursed.

437
00:20:41,601 --> 00:20:44,161
-Mum!
-This is another terrible omen for you.

438
00:20:44,601 --> 00:20:45,641
Thanks for that.

439
00:20:47,081 --> 00:20:49,161
I'll get the cart, bring his body back.

440
00:20:49,521 --> 00:20:51,721
I'll help you prepare the burial

441
00:20:52,441 --> 00:20:54,241
and pray for your family.

442
00:20:55,961 --> 00:20:57,121
UMBREEN: I don't know what to do

443
00:20:57,281 --> 00:20:58,801
Bhakti had agreed to marry us.

444
00:20:58,921 --> 00:21:02,001
And not many would agree
to a Hindu marrying a Muslim right now.

445
00:21:02,161 --> 00:21:04,281
Then you can't go ahead
with marrying Prem.

446
00:21:05,321 --> 00:21:07,041
UMBREEN: You think I'd give up
that easily?

447
00:21:07,481 --> 00:21:09,281
I've seen a war take our young,

448
00:21:09,641 --> 00:21:11,601
and drought take our old and weak.

449
00:21:11,721 --> 00:21:16,081
Now, men without a clue are imposing a
border like a crack through my country.

450
00:21:17,561 --> 00:21:19,601
Prem is the one certain thing
in my life.

451
00:21:21,881 --> 00:21:23,201
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

452
00:21:44,201 --> 00:21:45,841
This must be scrambling your head.

453
00:21:47,881 --> 00:21:48,881
Just a bit.

454
00:21:50,761 --> 00:21:52,321
I thought I knew my nan's story.

455
00:21:53,241 --> 00:21:54,481
She inspired me.

456
00:21:56,081 --> 00:21:58,401
But if this is true,
if this is her life,

457
00:21:59,441 --> 00:22:00,681
then she lied to me.

458
00:22:01,521 --> 00:22:02,521
(SIGHS)

459
00:22:03,281 --> 00:22:06,281
Yeah, but maybe she just didn't
want to tell you everything, you know?

460
00:22:07,361 --> 00:22:10,361
Woman's allowed to have secrets,
even from her granddaughter.

461
00:22:12,881 --> 00:22:15,441
And you've got to remember, Yaz,
that girl in there,

462
00:22:16,281 --> 00:22:17,721
she ain't your nan yet.

463
00:22:18,481 --> 00:22:21,041
It's only later
she'll decide how to tell it.

464
00:22:23,401 --> 00:22:26,001
And I honestly don't know whether
any of us know the real truth

465
00:22:26,161 --> 00:22:27,161
of our own lives.

466
00:22:27,401 --> 00:22:29,401
Because we're too busy living them
from the inside.

467
00:22:29,681 --> 00:22:31,241
So just enjoy, Yaz.

468
00:22:31,321 --> 00:22:33,881
Live this moment
and figure it out later.

469
00:22:35,841 --> 00:22:38,041
-Easier said then done.
-No, no, I get that, but...

470
00:22:40,561 --> 00:22:41,801
Look at us.

471
00:22:42,841 --> 00:22:44,641
The things we're doing with the Doc.

472
00:22:45,481 --> 00:22:46,961
We're in 1947.

473
00:22:47,801 --> 00:22:48,961
-With me nan.
-Yeah.

474
00:22:49,561 --> 00:22:50,761
No one will ever believe us.

475
00:22:51,681 --> 00:22:53,001
-Especially me nan.
-Exactly.

476
00:22:53,401 --> 00:22:54,921
RYAN: (SHOUTING) We've lost the doctor!

477
00:22:55,161 --> 00:22:56,801
Mayday! Red alert!

478
00:22:56,881 --> 00:22:57,961
-Sounds like trouble.
-RYAN: Red alert!

479
00:22:58,081 --> 00:22:59,121
It must be the Doc.

480
00:22:59,521 --> 00:23:00,561
(EXHALES SHARPLY)

481
00:23:02,761 --> 00:23:05,361
-We've lost the Doctor!
-She was with us and then gone!

482
00:23:08,881 --> 00:23:10,241
(PANTING)

483
00:23:10,561 --> 00:23:11,561
There she is!

484
00:23:12,681 --> 00:23:14,481
-Get to the barn!
-GRAHAM: What?

485
00:23:15,001 --> 00:23:16,721
Get to the barn, right now!

486
00:23:20,921 --> 00:23:22,241
-(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)
-(DEVICE BEEPS)

487
00:23:24,801 --> 00:23:26,161
-What are you...
-Shh.

488
00:23:28,121 --> 00:23:29,401
No, stay out!

489
00:23:29,761 --> 00:23:31,081
-(HIGH-PITCHED WHIRRING)
-(ALL GROANING)

490
00:23:34,561 --> 00:23:36,601
THIJARIAN: You disrupt our work.

491
00:23:37,041 --> 00:23:38,601
Good. Now, who are you here for?

492
00:23:39,161 --> 00:23:40,681
We don't answer to you.

493
00:23:40,761 --> 00:23:44,761
THIJARIAN 2: You must leave,
or we will stand over your corpses.

494
00:23:44,921 --> 00:23:46,561
Nothing like getting to the point.

495
00:23:46,641 --> 00:23:48,961
Is it me? Are you here to kill me?

496
00:23:49,081 --> 00:23:50,721
Take me and promise to leave the others.

497
00:23:50,921 --> 00:23:52,361
Prem, no, not going to happen.

498
00:23:52,441 --> 00:23:53,801
DOCTOR: Both of you,
I'm dealing with this.

499
00:23:53,961 --> 00:23:56,521
I've just nicked four of your
Transmat locks out of the forest.

500
00:23:56,601 --> 00:23:57,601
Good trick, by the way.

501
00:23:57,681 --> 00:23:59,841
Forcing people back,
away from the boundary. Clever.

502
00:24:00,121 --> 00:24:02,481
So clever,
I'm using it myself, against you,

503
00:24:02,841 --> 00:24:04,161
locking you out of this farm.

504
00:24:04,761 --> 00:24:06,361
-(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)
-(DEVICE BEEPS)

505
00:24:08,081 --> 00:24:09,081
You killed the demons.

506
00:24:09,561 --> 00:24:12,001
No, just exiled them for now.

507
00:24:12,441 --> 00:24:14,601
I made a temporary Transmat barrier
around the farm.

508
00:24:14,681 --> 00:24:16,881
I'm hoping it will keep them out
for the next few hours.

509
00:24:17,001 --> 00:24:19,961
Enough time for you to get married
and for us to keep everyone safe.

510
00:24:20,161 --> 00:24:21,521
Are you serious,
after what's just happened?

511
00:24:21,681 --> 00:24:23,921
Can't you see what's happening?
You bring demons to life.

512
00:24:24,201 --> 00:24:25,561
I don't think they're demons.

513
00:24:25,681 --> 00:24:27,321
Well, I do. I'm with Manish.

514
00:24:27,721 --> 00:24:28,721
How many hours?

515
00:24:29,201 --> 00:24:31,921
Twelve. Eighteen at a push.
I can't be sure.

516
00:24:32,641 --> 00:24:35,161
Tonight, we celebrate
and we marry first thing.

517
00:24:35,361 --> 00:24:37,281
And then if we have
to fight them, we will.

518
00:24:37,561 --> 00:24:38,881
Come on.

519
00:24:40,841 --> 00:24:41,841
(BARN DOOR OPENING)

520
00:24:42,361 --> 00:24:43,881
-(BARN DOOR CLOSES)
-Still not interfering, are we?

521
00:24:44,001 --> 00:24:46,561
Oi! The alien assassins started it.

522
00:24:46,761 --> 00:24:47,961
We can't leave now.

523
00:24:48,121 --> 00:24:51,961
If something happens to Umbreen,
your whole timeline could be erased.

524
00:24:52,121 --> 00:24:55,001
No Yaz! We can't have a universe
with no Yaz.

525
00:24:55,281 --> 00:24:57,641
Now, whatever's in here,

526
00:24:58,401 --> 00:24:59,641
might tell us more.

527
00:25:02,641 --> 00:25:04,081
Nobody breathe too deeply.

528
00:25:06,961 --> 00:25:08,081
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)

529
00:25:08,201 --> 00:25:09,481
-(DEVICE BEEPING)
-Whoa!

530
00:25:09,921 --> 00:25:11,961
It's overloaded my sonic!
Too many inputs.

531
00:25:12,201 --> 00:25:14,441
That's never happened before. Oh, think.

532
00:25:16,321 --> 00:25:17,321
Have to go analogue.

533
00:25:18,521 --> 00:25:21,241
I need oil, water, tree bark,

534
00:25:21,441 --> 00:25:25,081
a sauce pan, nine containers,
an old newspaper, a touch of ox spit,

535
00:25:25,321 --> 00:25:26,921
a chicken poo, and a biscuit.

536
00:25:27,241 --> 00:25:29,001
-Bagsy not chicken poo.
-Why a biscuit?

537
00:25:29,241 --> 00:25:30,241
I love biscuits!

538
00:25:40,601 --> 00:25:43,721
I am never, ever getting spit
from an ox ever again,

539
00:25:43,801 --> 00:25:45,441
-no matter how much you need it.
-(LAUGHS)

540
00:25:45,681 --> 00:25:47,441
The ox took a bit of a shine to him.

541
00:25:47,881 --> 00:25:48,881
(LIQUID BUBBLING)

542
00:25:53,121 --> 00:25:54,881
-So, what is it, then?
-Science.

543
00:25:55,041 --> 00:25:57,201
Should break the sample down.
Give us more information.

544
00:25:57,441 --> 00:25:58,801
Only take a couple of hours.

545
00:25:58,961 --> 00:25:59,961
(BARN DOOR CREAKS OPEN)

546
00:26:00,881 --> 00:26:02,121
Are you coming or not?

547
00:26:02,801 --> 00:26:03,801
What's that?

548
00:26:04,401 --> 00:26:05,961
Part of my, er, demon-repellent.

549
00:26:06,441 --> 00:26:08,241
-That better be gone by tomorrow.
-Definitely.

550
00:26:08,601 --> 00:26:10,281
So, come on, women with me and Mum,

551
00:26:10,361 --> 00:26:11,721
men over at Prem's house.

552
00:26:12,601 --> 00:26:14,521
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

553
00:26:14,641 --> 00:26:16,761
(BARN DOOR CREAKS OPEN)

554
00:26:34,201 --> 00:26:36,361
This is the best thing ever!

555
00:26:37,481 --> 00:26:38,881
Never did this when I was a man!

556
00:26:39,801 --> 00:26:40,801
(LAUGHS)

557
00:26:41,081 --> 00:26:43,041
Doctor, you and your jokes.

558
00:26:44,161 --> 00:26:45,361
Yeah, that's right.

559
00:26:45,481 --> 00:26:48,081
My references to body and gender
regeneration are all in jest.

560
00:26:48,161 --> 00:26:49,441
(LAUGHS NERVOUSLY)

561
00:26:49,521 --> 00:26:52,161
-I'm such a comedian.
-(LAUGHS UNCOMFORTABLY)

562
00:26:52,561 --> 00:26:54,521
Umbreen doesn't think
these are my best work.

563
00:26:55,321 --> 00:26:57,841
But, maybe if you had to prepare
a body this morning,

564
00:26:57,921 --> 00:26:59,481
you wouldn't draw so well either.

565
00:27:02,801 --> 00:27:05,561
So, how long have you known Prem?

566
00:27:05,961 --> 00:27:07,161
Our whole lives.

567
00:27:07,401 --> 00:27:08,681
We grew up here together.

568
00:27:09,441 --> 00:27:12,401
Our families have worked the land
alongside each other for generations.

569
00:27:13,761 --> 00:27:15,601
I can't believe it's happening.

570
00:27:15,921 --> 00:27:17,761
I waited so long for him.

571
00:27:18,281 --> 00:27:20,121
All the time he was away fighting,

572
00:27:20,641 --> 00:27:22,601
I was terrified he wouldn't come home.

573
00:27:22,961 --> 00:27:24,721
But, he did.

574
00:27:25,561 --> 00:27:28,161
And now I see my life mapped out
with him.

575
00:27:28,401 --> 00:27:29,921
Our home, here.

576
00:27:30,761 --> 00:27:32,281
If they let us stay.

577
00:27:33,641 --> 00:27:35,161
Nobody cares what we do here, Mum.

578
00:27:35,361 --> 00:27:37,481
-It's not a city.
-HASNA: I stood outside earlier.

579
00:27:37,761 --> 00:27:39,881
I heard gangs in the distance.

580
00:27:40,041 --> 00:27:41,761
Motor vehicles, gunshots.

581
00:27:42,761 --> 00:27:43,761
It's a long way away.

582
00:27:43,921 --> 00:27:45,321
It's not too late.

583
00:27:45,441 --> 00:27:47,481
I can still find you a good Muslim man.

584
00:27:48,441 --> 00:27:49,881
Are you joking right now?

585
00:27:50,521 --> 00:27:52,241
Look at the misery that follows him.

586
00:27:52,761 --> 00:27:54,561
You don't even have a priest.

587
00:27:54,801 --> 00:27:56,601
What sort of a respectable wedding
will it be?

588
00:27:56,761 --> 00:27:58,601
I don't care about traditions!

589
00:27:58,681 --> 00:28:00,401
I don't care about respectable...

590
00:28:01,041 --> 00:28:03,121
Wait. You're a doctor, right?

591
00:28:03,281 --> 00:28:04,361
That's respectable

592
00:28:04,721 --> 00:28:06,041
You could marry us.

593
00:28:06,121 --> 00:28:07,361
Don't be ridiculous!

594
00:28:07,601 --> 00:28:08,841
-I suppose I could.
-No.

595
00:28:09,001 --> 00:28:10,401
-Doctor!
-I haven't

596
00:28:10,481 --> 00:28:11,921
officiated a wedding since Einstein's.

597
00:28:12,001 --> 00:28:13,321
His parents didn't approve either.

598
00:28:13,641 --> 00:28:14,921
Non-denominational, though.

599
00:28:15,041 --> 00:28:16,521
If your father were alive,

600
00:28:17,001 --> 00:28:18,161
he'd die on the spot.

601
00:28:18,241 --> 00:28:20,321
Everyone is saying it's a new future.

602
00:28:20,401 --> 00:28:21,641
We make our own traditions now.

603
00:28:21,961 --> 00:28:22,961
You're on.

604
00:28:23,481 --> 00:28:24,961
I thought we were not getting involved.

605
00:28:25,201 --> 00:28:26,521
(SOFTLY) Only a teensy bit.

606
00:28:30,401 --> 00:28:31,401
Bust.

607
00:28:31,841 --> 00:28:32,841
Again.

608
00:28:33,321 --> 00:28:35,121
You're cleaning me out, little brother.

609
00:28:36,681 --> 00:28:38,241
You know what they say though, Prem.

610
00:28:38,401 --> 00:28:40,041
Unlucky at cards, lucky in love.

611
00:28:40,881 --> 00:28:42,801
-You think he's lucky?
-Yeah.

612
00:28:44,121 --> 00:28:46,801
-I think he's lost his mind.
-Hey, mate, not on his stag night.

613
00:28:47,241 --> 00:28:48,601
PREM: You'll have to forgive him.

614
00:28:49,161 --> 00:28:50,841
Spends too much time reading pamphlets.

615
00:28:51,881 --> 00:28:53,521
Listening to angry men on the radio.

616
00:28:54,961 --> 00:28:56,081
Do you love me, Prem?

617
00:28:56,721 --> 00:28:57,841
Of course I love you.

618
00:28:59,361 --> 00:29:02,121
Even if sometimes I don't recognise
the brother I left behind.

619
00:29:05,361 --> 00:29:06,481
Kunal would have understood.

620
00:29:08,801 --> 00:29:11,161
He said he was only fighting for you lot
so he could get rid of you.

621
00:29:11,241 --> 00:29:12,481
And now it's happening.

622
00:29:12,801 --> 00:29:14,001
(LAUGHS)

623
00:29:14,201 --> 00:29:15,241
Don't marry tomorrow.

624
00:29:15,561 --> 00:29:18,041
-Umbreen's a good woman.
-You can't live together here.

625
00:29:18,241 --> 00:29:19,681
India's not her home, now.

626
00:29:20,801 --> 00:29:22,321
India's a home to all of us.

627
00:29:23,081 --> 00:29:24,521
We didn't change when a line was drawn.

628
00:29:24,641 --> 00:29:25,681
But we did.

629
00:29:29,721 --> 00:29:30,761
I need air.

630
00:29:34,201 --> 00:29:36,561
(DOOR OPENS AND CLOSES)

631
00:29:40,681 --> 00:29:43,241
YASMIN: She's going to officiate
knowing he's not my granddad.

632
00:29:43,321 --> 00:29:44,921
Well, if Manish has anything
to do with it,

633
00:29:45,081 --> 00:29:46,521
there won't be anything to officiate.

634
00:29:46,681 --> 00:29:49,361
And these alien assassins,
we still don't know who they come for.

635
00:29:49,561 --> 00:29:51,921
(SIGHS) What happens here?

636
00:29:52,401 --> 00:29:54,601
Why did she never tell her family
about any of this?

637
00:29:56,921 --> 00:29:59,881
This just is the densest
organic material that you can imagine.

638
00:29:59,961 --> 00:30:01,241
It's sort of everything.

639
00:30:01,401 --> 00:30:05,081
Carbon, phosphorous, oxygen, nitrogen,

640
00:30:05,161 --> 00:30:06,881
sulphur, calcium.

641
00:30:07,601 --> 00:30:11,281
Billions of DNA fragments
and loads more.

642
00:30:12,121 --> 00:30:14,081
(TRANSMAT LOCKS BEEPING)

643
00:30:18,041 --> 00:30:19,481
They're breaking the Transmat locks!

644
00:30:23,441 --> 00:30:24,441
Doctor!

645
00:30:26,401 --> 00:30:27,761
(GASPS)

646
00:30:36,081 --> 00:30:37,081
DOCTOR: So, what?

647
00:30:37,801 --> 00:30:38,921
Is it me?

648
00:30:40,201 --> 00:30:41,561
You've come to assassinate me?

649
00:30:42,001 --> 00:30:45,161
-THIJARIAN: We are not assassins.
-DOCTOR: Firstly,

650
00:30:45,401 --> 00:30:47,441
I much prefer it when you're not
making the threatening sound.

651
00:30:47,601 --> 00:30:48,881
So thanks for that, at least.

652
00:30:49,281 --> 00:30:51,441
Secondly, don't lie to me.

653
00:30:52,961 --> 00:30:55,201
I know the stories
of the assassins of Thijar.

654
00:30:55,881 --> 00:30:58,241
-We have changed.
-What?

655
00:30:58,521 --> 00:30:59,721
Changed how?

656
00:31:00,241 --> 00:31:02,081
Our past is no more.

657
00:31:02,201 --> 00:31:04,041
We are no longer assassins.

658
00:31:04,121 --> 00:31:05,841
Now, we are witnesses.

659
00:31:06,641 --> 00:31:07,801
I don't understand.

660
00:31:08,641 --> 00:31:12,201
We honour the lost
as we cannot honour our own.

661
00:31:12,281 --> 00:31:13,921
No. Still not with you.

662
00:31:14,201 --> 00:31:15,921
As the assassins hunted,

663
00:31:16,321 --> 00:31:18,961
the Thijarian world was destroyed.

664
00:31:19,281 --> 00:31:20,881
We returned to find nothing.

665
00:31:25,081 --> 00:31:27,961
This is all that remains of our home.

666
00:31:28,681 --> 00:31:29,721
Our people.

667
00:31:30,441 --> 00:31:32,321
Every ancestor.

668
00:31:33,281 --> 00:31:36,001
All one dust.

669
00:31:36,921 --> 00:31:38,161
I didn't know.

670
00:31:39,801 --> 00:31:41,121
I'm so sorry.

671
00:31:41,521 --> 00:31:44,001
They died unwitnessed, unsaved.

672
00:31:44,241 --> 00:31:46,441
We were too late
to grieve or honour them.

673
00:31:47,001 --> 00:31:50,441
BOTH: But we who returned gave up
100 generations to sift,

674
00:31:50,841 --> 00:31:53,641
to remember the lost dead.
The unmourned.

675
00:31:54,121 --> 00:31:56,521
In time, it was all we knew.

676
00:31:56,601 --> 00:31:59,641
And now we travel beyond, seeking

677
00:31:59,881 --> 00:32:03,281
the unacknowledged dead
across all of time and space.

678
00:32:03,481 --> 00:32:05,961
This is now the Thijarian mission.

679
00:32:06,161 --> 00:32:08,721
To bear witness to those alone.

680
00:32:09,001 --> 00:32:11,401
To see. To bear pain.

681
00:32:11,561 --> 00:32:14,041
Honour life as it passes.

682
00:32:14,521 --> 00:32:17,921
As each one passes,
we commemorate union.

683
00:32:18,481 --> 00:32:22,441
That's what Prem saw you do to Kunal,
what you were doing to the holy man.

684
00:32:23,081 --> 00:32:25,441
But why here? Why now?

685
00:32:25,761 --> 00:32:27,361
Millions will perish,

686
00:32:27,561 --> 00:32:30,361
unseen, unknown,
in the days to come here.

687
00:32:30,681 --> 00:32:32,321
The casualties of Partition.

688
00:32:32,801 --> 00:32:33,961
BOTH: We read the time waves.

689
00:32:34,881 --> 00:32:36,601
But why this family?

690
00:32:36,761 --> 00:32:37,961
Why this land?

691
00:32:43,641 --> 00:32:45,601
(GASPS) Prem.

692
00:32:45,801 --> 00:32:47,201
His time is soon.

693
00:32:47,721 --> 00:32:48,721
How soon?

694
00:32:50,761 --> 00:32:53,561
Give him a day.
Just give him this day, please.

695
00:32:54,081 --> 00:32:55,721
BOTH: We are not gods.

696
00:32:56,041 --> 00:33:00,161
Events sit as they will.
We only witness.

697
00:33:00,881 --> 00:33:03,681
The fixed force of time
cannot be stopped.

698
00:33:03,961 --> 00:33:04,961
I know.

699
00:33:07,721 --> 00:33:09,641
If you didn't kill the holy man,

700
00:33:10,761 --> 00:33:12,841
if you were only honouring his death,

701
00:33:13,601 --> 00:33:14,801
how did he die?

702
00:33:15,721 --> 00:33:17,321
We can show you.

703
00:33:25,841 --> 00:33:27,641
(BOOMING)

704
00:33:27,721 --> 00:33:28,721
(GASPS)

705
00:33:30,881 --> 00:33:32,601
Where've you been?
You've been gone hours.

706
00:33:32,761 --> 00:33:34,601
The Thijarians, they told me everything.

707
00:33:35,041 --> 00:33:36,121
I know what happened.

708
00:33:37,161 --> 00:33:38,161
And I know what happens.

709
00:33:40,121 --> 00:33:41,521
I want to know what happens.

710
00:33:44,161 --> 00:33:45,441
Prem dies today.

711
00:33:50,801 --> 00:33:52,681
-We can't let that happen.
-It has to.

712
00:33:53,321 --> 00:33:54,961
For Umbreen to become your nani,

713
00:33:55,361 --> 00:33:57,801
for you to exist, Prem has to die.

714
00:33:59,561 --> 00:34:01,801
You mean, the Thijarians
have come to kill Prem?

715
00:34:02,001 --> 00:34:04,281
That's not why they're here.
They're not assassins.

716
00:34:04,561 --> 00:34:06,361
They honour those who die alone.

717
00:34:06,801 --> 00:34:07,921
Aliens with compassion.

718
00:34:08,121 --> 00:34:10,521
Umbreen loses her husband
on the day she marries.

719
00:34:12,081 --> 00:34:13,921
Of course
she never wants to talk about it.

720
00:34:14,481 --> 00:34:15,921
I'm sorry, Yaz.

721
00:34:16,321 --> 00:34:17,481
-We should leave.
-YASMIN: No.

722
00:34:17,801 --> 00:34:20,321
I want to be sure she's safe,
whatever happens.

723
00:34:20,561 --> 00:34:22,001
I want to look after my nani.

724
00:34:22,801 --> 00:34:23,801
I'm with Yaz.

725
00:34:25,121 --> 00:34:26,121
Yeah, me, too.

726
00:34:29,841 --> 00:34:31,321
We can't tell them what we know.

727
00:34:31,401 --> 00:34:32,401
(RADIO STATIC)

728
00:34:32,681 --> 00:34:34,401
MAN 1: (ON RADIO) My friends,
I woke this morning

729
00:34:34,761 --> 00:34:36,601
to the sight of smoke over the hills.

730
00:34:36,721 --> 00:34:38,281
More villages burned.

731
00:34:38,361 --> 00:34:41,041
More homes ransacked.

732
00:34:41,161 --> 00:34:44,601
It seems these savage mobs
cannot be satisfied.

733
00:34:44,761 --> 00:34:45,921
(RADIO STATIC)

734
00:34:46,081 --> 00:34:48,561
MAN 2: (ON RADIO)
I urge you to stay safe and stay strong.

735
00:34:49,441 --> 00:34:51,201
Protect yourselves however you must.

736
00:35:02,601 --> 00:35:03,601
Oh.

737
00:35:04,441 --> 00:35:05,881
The flowers don't help much.

738
00:35:06,001 --> 00:35:07,921
You still look
like a schoolboy on manoeuvres.

739
00:35:08,361 --> 00:35:09,481
These are the best clothes I have.

740
00:35:09,881 --> 00:35:10,881
You look great.

741
00:35:11,761 --> 00:35:12,961
No Manish?

742
00:35:14,881 --> 00:35:16,321
He was out early.

743
00:35:17,081 --> 00:35:18,281
He'll be here.

744
00:35:19,041 --> 00:35:21,081
Did you hear the noises in the valley
during the night?

745
00:35:22,761 --> 00:35:24,041
Violence is getting closer.

746
00:35:27,761 --> 00:35:29,241
Who's doing this stuff?

747
00:35:30,721 --> 00:35:34,361
Ordinary people
who've lived here all their lives.

748
00:35:35,561 --> 00:35:37,601
Whipped into a frenzy
to be part of a mob.

749
00:35:40,361 --> 00:35:43,001
And nothing worse than when
normal people lose their minds.

750
00:35:44,641 --> 00:35:46,841
We've lived together for decades.

751
00:35:46,921 --> 00:35:48,921
Hindu, Muslim and Sikh.

752
00:35:50,561 --> 00:35:54,241
And now we're being told our differences
are more important than what unites us.

753
00:35:54,881 --> 00:35:56,481
Like we learned nothing in the war.

754
00:36:00,001 --> 00:36:01,921
I don't know how we'll protect people

755
00:36:02,441 --> 00:36:04,401
when hatred's coming from all sides.

756
00:36:07,081 --> 00:36:08,081
Well,

757
00:36:09,521 --> 00:36:11,201
all we can strive to be

758
00:36:13,921 --> 00:36:14,961
is good men.

759
00:36:22,881 --> 00:36:24,321
And you, Prem,

760
00:36:26,801 --> 00:36:27,961
are a good man.

761
00:36:30,681 --> 00:36:31,681
(SNIFFLES)

762
00:36:35,241 --> 00:36:36,761
(SIGHS) I, erm...

763
00:36:39,641 --> 00:36:40,721
I, er...

764
00:36:41,321 --> 00:36:42,321
Come on.

765
00:36:42,961 --> 00:36:43,961
Marriage.

766
00:36:45,201 --> 00:36:46,201
(SIGHS)

767
00:36:48,481 --> 00:36:50,041
This is the spot you choose?

768
00:36:50,961 --> 00:36:53,321
I'm going to be
the first woman married in Pakistan.

769
00:36:54,241 --> 00:36:55,561
-Of course, you are.
-(LAUGHS)

770
00:36:57,121 --> 00:36:58,201
(SIGHS)

771
00:36:58,881 --> 00:36:59,921
(SOBS GENTLY)

772
00:37:00,321 --> 00:37:01,561
You all right, sweetheart?

773
00:37:02,681 --> 00:37:04,041
I always cry at weddings.

774
00:37:08,281 --> 00:37:09,481
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)

775
00:37:12,561 --> 00:37:14,641
I know there aren't many certainties
in any of our lives,

776
00:37:16,481 --> 00:37:18,481
but, Umbreen, Prem

777
00:37:19,841 --> 00:37:22,561
what I see in you is
the certainty of having each other.

778
00:37:24,321 --> 00:37:26,161
Something I believe in my faith,

779
00:37:27,281 --> 00:37:28,321
love,

780
00:37:29,561 --> 00:37:30,961
in all its forms,

781
00:37:31,401 --> 00:37:33,481
is the most powerful weapon we have.

782
00:37:34,281 --> 00:37:36,041
Because love is a form of hope,

783
00:37:36,161 --> 00:37:38,601
and like hope, love abides.

784
00:37:39,841 --> 00:37:41,241
In the face of everything,

785
00:37:42,681 --> 00:37:44,321
you both found love with each other.

786
00:37:44,641 --> 00:37:48,841
You believed in it, you fought for it,
and you waited for it.

787
00:37:49,321 --> 00:37:52,441
And, now, you're committing to it.

788
00:37:53,921 --> 00:37:57,561
Which makes you, right now,
the two strongest people on this planet.

789
00:37:58,681 --> 00:38:00,121
Maybe in this universe.

790
00:38:04,321 --> 00:38:05,841
I'm not sure how we formalise this.

791
00:38:06,961 --> 00:38:07,961
(LAUGHS) I am.

792
00:38:12,241 --> 00:38:13,241
Will you?

793
00:38:18,241 --> 00:38:21,361
That's a Hindu thing, isn't it?
Tying the hands together.

794
00:38:23,561 --> 00:38:24,761
Now it can be our thing.

795
00:38:25,401 --> 00:38:26,641
If we want it to be.

796
00:38:38,681 --> 00:38:40,041
UMBREEN: I'm not often lost for words,

797
00:38:40,561 --> 00:38:42,601
but I never thought this day would come.

798
00:38:43,081 --> 00:38:44,481
It's been tough.

799
00:38:46,041 --> 00:38:47,801
People who I wish were here
to celebrate...

800
00:38:48,761 --> 00:38:49,761
They are, Beti.

801
00:38:50,841 --> 00:38:52,321
UMBREEN: The drought
was nearly the end of us.

802
00:38:53,201 --> 00:38:55,961
But we get to have this day
because of Manish.

803
00:38:56,601 --> 00:38:58,321
You were tireless.

804
00:38:58,561 --> 00:39:00,961
When there was hardly any food,
you took none.

805
00:39:01,561 --> 00:39:03,681
When we doubted we'd make it
through to summer,

806
00:39:03,961 --> 00:39:05,281
you kept on.

807
00:39:06,121 --> 00:39:08,521
Night and day,
we worked these fields together.

808
00:39:09,361 --> 00:39:11,601
I am proud to have been your neighbour.

809
00:39:11,681 --> 00:39:14,201
But I'm even prouder, now,
to call you my brother.

810
00:39:16,601 --> 00:39:18,241
You kept us fed, Manish.

811
00:39:21,841 --> 00:39:23,081
Will you let me feed you?

812
00:39:31,881 --> 00:39:34,001
I didn't work this land
for you, Umbreen.

813
00:39:35,201 --> 00:39:36,601
I worked it for my brothers.

814
00:39:37,761 --> 00:39:39,201
One who didn't come back,

815
00:39:39,841 --> 00:39:40,961
and the other I wish hadn't.

816
00:39:41,721 --> 00:39:42,801
-Enough, Manish.
-No

817
00:39:45,281 --> 00:39:46,281
Look at you all.

818
00:39:46,921 --> 00:39:48,361
Don't you understand what's coming?

819
00:39:49,681 --> 00:39:51,121
None of this will make a difference.

820
00:39:57,481 --> 00:39:58,601
I'LL talk to him.

821
00:40:03,001 --> 00:40:04,761
Prem, your turn.

822
00:40:07,721 --> 00:40:08,841
Okay.

823
00:40:09,041 --> 00:40:10,521
-(BARN DOOR CLOSES)
-So...

824
00:40:11,641 --> 00:40:14,041
-And what are you doing?
-You did a Hindu thing with the rope.

825
00:40:15,761 --> 00:40:17,801
Only right I do a Muslim thing, too.

826
00:40:20,281 --> 00:40:21,481
This is your mahr.

827
00:40:22,241 --> 00:40:23,681
Yours to keep forever.

828
00:40:26,041 --> 00:40:27,041
Prem.

829
00:40:30,801 --> 00:40:31,801
I'm sorry.

830
00:40:32,881 --> 00:40:33,881
Cursed.

831
00:40:36,201 --> 00:40:37,201
It's fine.

832
00:40:38,281 --> 00:40:39,281
It's perfect.

833
00:40:40,201 --> 00:40:41,601
This is us, forever.

834
00:40:42,601 --> 00:40:44,041
Our moment in time.

835
00:40:53,201 --> 00:40:55,001
Is that what you used
to shoot the holy man?

836
00:40:55,881 --> 00:40:57,601
-Your brother's rifle?
-(RIFLE CLICKS)

837
00:40:57,761 --> 00:40:58,761
Be quiet.

838
00:40:59,081 --> 00:41:00,161
What happened, Manish?

839
00:41:00,801 --> 00:41:02,121
Did it get out of hand?

840
00:41:02,601 --> 00:41:04,001
Did you scare yourself?

841
00:41:04,201 --> 00:41:07,121
Because you were too young for the war.
You've never fought or killed anyone.

842
00:41:07,201 --> 00:41:09,321
I'm not scared of anything
because this is my time to fight.

843
00:41:10,641 --> 00:41:11,961
Fight for what I believe

844
00:41:12,361 --> 00:41:15,321
Killing a man because he might
marry a Muslim and a Hindu

845
00:41:15,401 --> 00:41:16,761
and then pretend you knew nothing?

846
00:41:17,321 --> 00:41:18,321
Take your friends and leave

847
00:41:20,001 --> 00:41:21,121
if you want to get out alive.

848
00:41:22,321 --> 00:41:23,521
What have you done? Who's coming?

849
00:41:23,721 --> 00:41:24,721
(HORSE WHINNYING)

850
00:41:25,481 --> 00:41:26,961
-(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)
-(GASPS)

851
00:41:27,241 --> 00:41:28,241
The future.

852
00:41:42,641 --> 00:41:44,361
(PANTING)

853
00:41:55,121 --> 00:41:56,521
Listen, all of you,

854
00:41:56,601 --> 00:41:59,361
there's armed men heading up the track.
You have to leave now.

855
00:42:00,081 --> 00:42:01,241
They want the land?

856
00:42:01,321 --> 00:42:04,121
I'm not going anywhere. This is my home.

857
00:42:04,521 --> 00:42:06,161
My husband and parents are buried here.

858
00:42:06,241 --> 00:42:07,761
I'm not going to abandon it to thugs.

859
00:42:07,841 --> 00:42:08,841
Where's Manish?

860
00:42:08,961 --> 00:42:12,001
He's leading them here.
He killed the holy man with your rifle.

861
00:42:13,601 --> 00:42:14,601
Of course.

862
00:42:14,761 --> 00:42:17,601
Mum"s right. This is our home. We stay.

863
00:42:17,881 --> 00:42:19,361
If you stay, you'll die.

864
00:42:19,721 --> 00:42:20,721
(GASPS)

865
00:42:21,121 --> 00:42:22,121
(SIGHS)

866
00:42:22,201 --> 00:42:23,641
Go to the house.

867
00:42:24,281 --> 00:42:25,961
Get anything essential,
and get back here.

868
00:42:27,921 --> 00:42:28,921
I'll help you.

869
00:42:30,761 --> 00:42:31,801
(BARN DOOR OPENS)

870
00:42:34,641 --> 00:42:35,641
(BARN DOOR CLOSES)

871
00:42:55,961 --> 00:42:57,321
Is that Sheffield

872
00:42:57,601 --> 00:42:58,601
marked on here?

873
00:42:58,721 --> 00:43:00,841
UMBREEN: My dad brought that map
home from the market one day.

874
00:43:01,081 --> 00:43:02,081
One night I said,

875
00:43:02,201 --> 00:43:05,361
"I'll put my finger on this map
and wherever it lands, I'm going to go."”

876
00:43:06,161 --> 00:43:07,361
And you landed on Sheffield?

877
00:43:08,041 --> 00:43:10,841
Such an exotic word. It's in England.
Do you know it?

878
00:43:11,081 --> 00:43:12,961
Stop talking. We have to leave.

879
00:43:25,641 --> 00:43:27,801
They're nearly here.
You need to move out.

880
00:43:27,921 --> 00:43:29,561
-I have to talk to Manish.
-No, Prem.

881
00:43:29,721 --> 00:43:30,961
I'm not leaving you here.

882
00:43:31,041 --> 00:43:32,921
I'll distract them long enough
to be sure you can get away.

883
00:43:33,561 --> 00:43:34,561
Then I'll be right behind you.

884
00:43:34,801 --> 00:43:35,841
It's too dangerous.

885
00:43:36,081 --> 00:43:37,081
He's my brother.

886
00:43:38,121 --> 00:43:41,321
Across the field, over the border,
into the forest. Keep going north.

887
00:43:42,881 --> 00:43:45,161
(SOBBING)

888
00:43:54,041 --> 00:43:55,041
Go.

889
00:43:58,961 --> 00:43:59,961
(BARN DOOR CLOSES)

890
00:44:01,161 --> 00:44:02,761
-You as well.
-I'll come with you.

891
00:44:03,441 --> 00:44:04,441
No.

892
00:44:06,921 --> 00:44:08,681
These are demons I have to face alone.

893
00:44:26,481 --> 00:44:28,561
UMBREEN: Mum! Come on, keep up.

894
00:44:28,681 --> 00:44:30,681
HASNA: I'm running as fast as I can!

895
00:44:45,841 --> 00:44:47,121
Look!

896
00:44:52,281 --> 00:44:54,481
They're checking their land
for people who don't belong.

897
00:44:56,681 --> 00:44:58,241
This is our home.

898
00:44:58,921 --> 00:45:00,241
Everyone's welcome here.

899
00:45:07,961 --> 00:45:09,481
I know what you did to the holy man.

900
00:45:11,481 --> 00:45:13,841
There's nothing holy about a man
who would approve your union.

901
00:45:14,641 --> 00:45:16,521
Better he die than defile himself.

902
00:45:18,361 --> 00:45:20,161
My baby brother,

903
00:45:21,441 --> 00:45:23,081
what happened to you?

904
00:45:25,401 --> 00:45:26,521
Really?

905
00:45:27,761 --> 00:45:28,961
I know you.

906
00:45:31,081 --> 00:45:32,321
We fought together in Siam.

907
00:45:33,841 --> 00:45:35,841
We made a good team. And now this?

908
00:45:40,201 --> 00:45:41,441
I can't let them through, Brother.

909
00:45:43,161 --> 00:45:44,481
We are your people, Prem.

910
00:45:45,201 --> 00:45:47,921
India's your country.
You and Kunal fought for this.

911
00:45:49,881 --> 00:45:51,281
This is not what I fought for.

912
00:46:03,601 --> 00:46:05,521
BOTH: We will watch over him now.

913
00:46:11,521 --> 00:46:12,641
Please, Manish.

914
00:46:25,961 --> 00:46:26,961
Come on.

915
00:46:36,681 --> 00:46:38,041
(GUN FIRES)

916
00:47:27,681 --> 00:47:29,121
She made it out, right?

917
00:47:30,681 --> 00:47:32,201
She got to Lahore?

918
00:47:34,201 --> 00:47:35,201
She lived?

919
00:47:36,241 --> 00:47:37,281
She made it.

920
00:47:51,281 --> 00:47:53,121
This is a terrible design.

921
00:47:54,441 --> 00:47:55,841
Was it a good wedding, at least?

922
00:47:58,521 --> 00:47:59,521
Yeah.

923
00:48:01,641 --> 00:48:02,841
What is the matter, Beti?

924
00:48:04,241 --> 00:48:05,401
You loved Granddad, didn't you?

925
00:48:05,961 --> 00:48:06,961
Of course.

926
00:48:07,161 --> 00:48:09,041
And you're happy
with how your life turned out?

927
00:48:09,841 --> 00:48:11,881
Why would you be asking that?

928
00:48:12,681 --> 00:48:16,041
Just, your journey, so many countries.

929
00:48:17,041 --> 00:48:18,401
So many years.

930
00:48:20,721 --> 00:48:23,121
I can't even begin to imagine
what you've dealt with.

931
00:48:25,201 --> 00:48:27,241
Then you end up in Sheffield,
of all places.

932
00:48:27,841 --> 00:48:29,561
I love Sheffield!

933
00:48:30,121 --> 00:48:31,121
Really?

934
00:48:32,401 --> 00:48:35,761
Well, not quite as exotic
as I thought it would be.

935
00:48:35,841 --> 00:48:40,321
-(CHUCKLES)
-But, it gave us stability,

936
00:48:41,361 --> 00:48:44,361
a life, a home.

937
00:48:46,721 --> 00:48:48,561
And it gave me your mum.

938
00:48:49,481 --> 00:48:52,241
And it gave me you and your sister.

939
00:48:55,841 --> 00:48:57,081
You want to know about the watch?

940
00:48:59,081 --> 00:49:00,201
Really?

941
00:49:03,121 --> 00:49:04,441
No.

942
00:49:04,961 --> 00:49:06,281
Tell me another time.

943
00:49:09,161 --> 00:49:10,521
I love you, Nani.

944
00:49:12,841 --> 00:49:15,321
And I love you too, Beti.

945
00:49:21,601 --> 00:49:23,601
(MUSIC PLAYING)

946
00:49:51,361 --> 00:49:52,801
Delivery for the Doctor.

947
00:49:53,121 --> 00:49:55,081
DOCTOR: Something is very wrong here
at Kerblam.

948
00:49:55,601 --> 00:49:56,841
If anything happens to us,

949
00:49:57,561 --> 00:49:58,601
or anyone else here,

950
00:49:59,321 --> 00:50:01,081
you'll have me to answer to.

